# Project structure

Three distinct execution contexts. Keep them separate — code that runs in one MUST NOT be imported into another except through the documented boundaries.

```
src/
  main/           # Electron main process (Node). App lifecycle, windows, native APIs, IPC handlers.
    index.ts      # App entry — app.whenReady(), createWindow(), event wiring.
    windows/      # BrowserWindow factories, one per window type.
    ipc/          # ipcMain.handle() registrations. One file per logical channel group.
    services/     # Main-process side effects (fs, child_process, native modules, network when sensitive).
    menu.ts       # Application menu (macOS-style).
  preload/        # Preload scripts. The ONLY bridge between main and renderer.
    index.ts      # contextBridge.exposeInMainWorld('api', ...)
  renderer/       # React app. Treat as a sandboxed web app.
    main.tsx      # React root.
    App.tsx
    components/
    hooks/
    state/
    styles/
  shared/         # Pure TypeScript shared between contexts.
    ipc-contracts.ts  # Channel names + request/response types. Source of truth for IPC.
    types.ts
build/            # Icons (icns), entitlements.plist, notarization config.
forge.config.ts   # Electron Forge config.
vite.*.config.ts  # Vite configs (one per context if needed).
```

## Rules
- `renderer/` MUST NOT `import` from `main/` or `preload/`. Renderer talks to main only via `window.api` exposed in preload.
- `main/` MUST NOT `import` from `renderer/`. Shared types live in `shared/`.
- `preload/` MUST NOT import heavy main-process modules. Preload is small and fast — it only wires the bridge.
- `shared/` is pure TS: no Node APIs, no DOM APIs, no React. Types + pure helpers only.
- Never put secrets, file paths, or environment-dependent constants in `renderer/`. Surface them from main via IPC.
